==========================================================================================
  CONSENSUS: Does style drift directionally with time?
==========================================================================================

  MANTEL TEST:
    Positive Mantel r (style distance grows with time gap): 22/22
    Significant (p < 0.05): 9/22
    → Stylistic distance between books INCREASES with chronological separation
    → Consistent with Hypothesis A (annual/drift composition)

  DBC ANCHOR:
    Negative r (later books closer to DBC): 22/22
    Significant (p < 0.05): 18/22
    → Later DBG books are closer to late-Caesar DBC
    → Consistent with Hypothesis A (annual composition)

  PCA PC1:
    Significant ordering along PC1 (p < 0.05): 4/11
    → Books are not randomly ordered in PC space

  OVERALL:
    Total tests: 55
    Total significant (p < 0.05): 31
    All tests use exact permutation (5,040 enumerations each)
    Bootstrap CIs account for small-n uncertainty

  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │ VERDICT: Evidence SUPPORTS Hypothesis A (annual / serial composition).            │
  │ Stylistic signal drifts directionally with time across multiple                  │
  │ feature representations and distance metrics.                                │
  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  CAVEATS:
    - n = 7. Every finding is a correlation over 7 data points.
    - Content-topic confound: books differ in subject matter.
    - Book length varies (4.1K–12.7K tokens). Short books have noisier features.
    - The Mantel test is sensitive to distance metric choice.
    - 'Significant' at p < 0.05 means ≤252/5040 permutations produce an equal or more extreme result.

